IPv6 Support

IPv6 Support in Eggdrop

  Eggdrop has full IPv6 support and is compiled with it by default. IPv6
  support allows Eggdrop to make and accept connections over IPv6
  networks. Every type of TCP connection can use IPv6, including IRC
  connections, DCC, file transfers, botnet links, Tcl script connections,
  telnet, and ident lookups.

REQUIREMENTS

  To use IPv6:

  - Your operating system must support IPv6
  - You must have IPv6 connectivity (either native or via tunneling)
  - Your IRC server must support IPv6 connections

  Most modern operating systems have IPv6 support out of the box:
  - Linux 2.4+ with full IPv6 support
  - macOS with full IPv6 support
  - FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD with full IPv6 support
  - Windows Vista and later (limitations on XP)
  - Cygwin 1.7+ (earlier versions have no IPv6 support)

USAGE

  IPv6 addresses can be used wherever IPv4 addresses are used. For
  server connections, IRC servers, DCC, and botnet links, simply use an
  IPv6 address instead of an IPv4 address:

    [[servers]]
    host = "irc.example.com"        # hostname (IPv4 or IPv6)
    host = "2001:db8::1"            # IPv6 literal address
    host = "[2001:db8::1]"          # IPv6 with port separator

  When an IPv6 address contains colons (:), enclose it in square
  brackets to prevent the colon from being interpreted as a port
  separator. This is necessary only when the port must be explicitly
  specified in the same setting.

CTCP CHAT4/CHAT6 COMMANDS

  When a user sends a CTCP CHAT request, the request passes through the
  IRC server, which hides the user's actual IP address. Since Eggdrop
  cannot determine whether the user is using IPv4 or IPv6, it must guess
  which type of address to send back.

  To work around this ambiguity:

  - Use CHAT4 to force an IPv4 DCC connection
  - Use CHAT6 to force an IPv6 DCC connection
  - Use CHAT for automatic detection (usually defaults to IPv4)

  Example from IRC:

    /ctcp bot CHAT6

  This forces Eggdrop to present an IPv6 address for the DCC connection.

CONFIGURATION SETTINGS

  The following settings in eggdrop.toml control IPv6 behavior:

  vhost4 (string)

    Set this to use a specific virtual host (bind address) for IPv4
    connections. Can contain either an IPv4 address or a hostname that
    resolves to an IPv4 address.

    Example:
      vhost4 = "192.0.2.1"

  vhost6 (string)

    Set this to use a specific virtual host (bind address) for IPv6
    connections. Can contain either an IPv6 address or a hostname that
    resolves to an IPv6 address.

    Example:
      vhost6 = "2001:db8::1"

  prefer-ipv6 (integer)

    When a connection can be established through both IPv4 and IPv6,
    set this to control which protocol is preferred:

      0 - Prefer IPv4 (default)
      1 - Prefer IPv6

    Example:
      prefer-ipv6 = 1

BOTNET OVER IPv6

  Botnet connections can use IPv6. In the hub's eggdrop.toml, configure
  an IPv6 listening port:

    listen = ["*" 4400]      # IPv4
    listen = ["[::1]" 4400]  # IPv6 (localhost)
    listen = ["::" 4400]     # IPv6 (all interfaces)

  Then, in the leaf bot's configuration, add the hub with an IPv6
  address:

    [[botnet]]
    handle = "HubBot"
    address = "2001:db8::1"
    port = 4400

COMPATIBILITY NOTES

  - IPv4 and IPv6 connections can coexist on the same Eggdrop instance
  - DNS resolution automatically uses both IPv4 and IPv6 records
  - Older IRC clients may not support IPv6 DCC
  - Some firewalls may block IPv6—ensure your network allows it

